ve to outsiders. The result has been a standardized, interchangeable system of education not overly demanding for either students or teachers, one that involved parents and local voters in its governance and finance. Innovative in its focus on bottom-up processes generated by individual behaviors rather than top-down decisions by bureaucrats, Making the Grade provides a new perspective on education reform that emphasizes how public schools form the basis for the localized social capital in American towns and cities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEducationxEconomic aspectszUnited States. 0aEducational changezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aSchool districtszUnited StatesxFinance. 0aSchool districtszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh  ahousing market, school districts, education, public schooling, local, homebuyers, economics, community, neighborhood, reform, social capital, history, finance, mobility, property, values, wealth, land policies, consolidation, labor, agriculture, geography, urban, class, nonfiction, segregation, charter, magnet, standardized tests, ap, ib, dual enrollment, college, success, students.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022625130140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226251318423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226251318/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles